\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Remote Access Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall establish and document usage restrictions and configuration requirements for each type of remote access allowed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Authorization
\series default
:
 The IT Director must explicitly authorize each remote access connection type prior to use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Managed Access Points
\series default
:
 Network Administrators shall route all remote access traffic through authorized and managed network access control points (e.g.,
 VPN Gateways).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Encryption
\series default
:
 System Administrators shall configure all remote access sessions to employ FIPS-validated cryptographic mechanisms (e.g.,
 TLS 1.2+,
 IPsec) to protect confidentiality and integrity in transit,
 consistent with the cryptographic standards established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Privileged Access
\series default
:
 Users shall not execute privileged commands via remote access unless the IT Director has documented a compelling operational need in accordance with AC-17(4).
 Such access shall require automated generation of assessable evidence (logging).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Session Termination
\series default
:
 Remote access sessions shall be configured to automatically terminate after twelve (12) hours of duration or fifteen (15) minutes of inactivity.
 Remote access sessions utilizing certificate-based authentication on devices located within a secure Criminal Justice Conveyance (e.g.,
 patrol vehicles) are exempt from the fifteen (15)-minute inactivity timeout to ensure officer safety.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Wireless Networking Security
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall manage all wireless access to Elko County networks in strict accordance with CJIS and NIST standards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Validation and Inventory
\series default
:
 Network Administrators shall perform validation testing quarterly to verify rogue APs do not exist and maintain a complete inventory of all APs.
 Network Administrators shall test AP range boundaries to determine the precise extent of wireless coverage and shall design AP coverage areas to be strictly limited to approved operational boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Physical and Logical Security
\series default
:
 APs shall be placed in secured areas to prevent unauthorized physical access and user manipulation.
 Network Administrators shall virtually insulate the wireless network from the wired operational infrastructure using boundary protection devices (e.g.,
 VLANs and ACLs),
 limiting access between wireless and wired networks to operational needs only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Required Protocol
\series default
:
 Wireless access to County internal networks shall use WPA2 or WPA3 Enterprise authentication and encryption.
 All encryption key sizes shall be at least 128-bits,
 and default shared keys shall be replaced by unique keys.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prohibited Protocols
\series default
:
 Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) and Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) original shall not be used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Configuration Baselines
\series default
:
 Network Administrators shall change default SSIDs,
 disable ad hoc mode,
 disable all nonessential management protocols,
 and utilize FIPS-compliant protocols (e.g.,
 SFTP,
 HTTPS,
 SNMP over TLS) for all management access.
 Non-FIPS compliant management access shall be disabled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
AP Reset Procedures
\series default
:
 The AP reset function shall be used only when necessary and shall be invoked only by authorized personnel.
 Following any reset,
 APs shall be restored to the latest approved security configuration baselines;
 factory default configurations shall not be utilized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
AP Logging
\series default
:
 AP logging shall be enabled on all access points.
 Access points incapable of logging shall not be deployed without a formal Risk Acceptance Memo approved by the IT Director.
 Logs shall be reviewed on a recurring basis at minimum monthly,
 consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Mobile Hotspots
\series default
:
 If a County mobile device authorized to access CJI is used as a Wi-Fi hotspot,
 it must employ encryption,
 utilize a strong pre-shared key,
 enable port filtering,
 and allow connections only from agency-controlled devices.
 Because mobile hotspots are limited in providing infrastructure-grade device authentication,
 CJI shall not be transmitted or exposed on the hotspot network without appropriate application-layer encryption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Mobile Device Management (MDM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All County-owned mobile devices accessing CJI or County data must be managed via a centralized MDM solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Mandatory Controls
\series default
:
 System Administrators shall configure the MDM to enforce remote locking,
 remote wiping,
 detection of jailbroken or rooted devices with automatic access blocking,
 folder- and disk-level encryption,
 and automatic device wiping after a maximum of ten (10) failed access attempts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Device Patching
\series default
:
 System Administrators shall apply critical security patches to mobile operating systems within fifteen (15) days of vendor release,
 consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.

\series default
 Deferrals require a formal Risk Acceptance Memo approved by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Encryption
\series default
:
 Full-device encryption shall be employed on all mobile devices authorized to process,
 store,
 or transmit CJI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Bluetooth
\series default
:
 Bluetooth capabilities on CJI-authorized mobile devices shall be disabled or restricted via MDM policy unless explicitly required for an approved operational purpose.
 Any authorized Bluetooth configuration shall restrict associations to known and agency-approved accessories only.
 Users shall not have the ability to create unapproved Bluetooth associations on CJI-capable devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prohibited Transmission Methods
\series default
:
 SMS,
 MMS,
 and consumer VoIP or chat applications (e.g.,
 FaceTime,
 standard SMS) shall not be used for the transmission of CJI.
 Any application-based communication used for CJI transmission must employ authentication and encryption mechanisms compliant with CJIS requirements,
 independent of the device PIN or password.
 VoIP applications are not granted the voice communication exemptions applicable to traditional cellular voice under CJIS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Cryptographic Key Protections
\series default
:
 Any certificates or cryptographic keys stored on mobile devices shall include protections against extraction from the device.
 Certificates or keys that grant special access or unique device identification shall be configured for remote wipe on demand or self-deletion upon a defined number of unsuccessful access attempts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Identification and Authentication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All mobile and remote access usage shall comply with the strict identification and authentication requirements defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Local Device Authentication:

\series default
 When mobile devices are authorized for CJI access,
 local device authentication shall be used to unlock the device.
 The authenticator used shall meet the minimum requirements defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Advanced Authentication (AA)
\series default
:
 Multi-factor authentication shall be used for all remote access to CJI and all privileged remote access.
 If a specific mobile scenario cannot support AA,
 the IT Director (LASO) must approve compensating controls prior to implementation in accordance with CJIS Security Policy IA-2(1) and IA-2(2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Session Lock
\series default
:
 Devices shall be configured to automatically initiate a pattern-hiding display lock after a maximum of fifteen (15) minutes of inactivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Mobile Device Incident Response
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
In addition to the incident response requirements in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 specific reporting procedures shall apply to mobile device operating scenarios.
 Users shall immediately report the loss,
 theft,
 or suspected compromise of any County mobile device to the Assistant IT Director.
 If a lost,
 stolen,
 or compromised device is authorized to access CJI,
 the incident shall be reported to the IT Director (LASO) immediately and no later than one (1) hour after discovery.
 Enhanced incident handling procedures shall address,
 at minimum,
 the following tiered scenarios:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device known to be locked,
 loss of physical control for less than fifteen (15) minutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device known to be locked,
 loss of physical control for fifteen (15) minutes or greater.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device lock state unknown,
 loss of physical control for less than fifteen (15) minutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device lock state unknown,
 loss of physical control for fifteen (15) minutes or greater.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device known to be unlocked,
 any loss of physical control exceeding five (5) minutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Total loss of device.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device compromise or suspected compromise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device loss or compromise outside the United States.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Upon notification of device loss,
 theft,
 or compromise,
 the System Administrator shall initiate remote lock and remote wipe procedures via the MDM platform without delay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 International Travel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Devices authorized to access CJI shall not be transported outside the United States unless explicitly authorized in writing by the IT Director.
 If authorized,
 the Assistant IT Director shall perform a pre-departure inspection to verify all controls are functioning properly,
 and a post-return inspection immediately upon the device's return to County custody.
 Any device returned from international travel that was connected to foreign cellular networks or foreign wireless infrastructure shall be subject to a security assessment prior to being returned to operational use,
 consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

